'''Nullification''' is an anomalous phenomenon that occurs when any type of matter is exposed to '''The Void'''. This process exists as a mechanism for The Void to maintain its emptiness. Matter introduced to The Void immediately begins to destabilize and, over time, decomposes. Unstable matter will decompose at an accelerated rate.

While the origins of this phenomenon remain debated, the earliest known cases of Nullification date back to the 1800s, with reports of objects and people vanishing after noclipping or discovering entrances to The Void.

For a long time, cases of Nullification were rare and largely unnoticed within '''The Backrooms''' until [[Incident 04-21-18]]. However, the phenomenon was not formally documented until after [[The Limina Mass Extinction]].

Although The Void itself is not inherently hazardous, matter, due to its properties, is incompatible with it. Upon exposure, matter unravels, becoming unstable before ultimately being erased.

Much about this process remains unconfirmed due to the challenges of investigating The Void. Some theories suggest that matter is not entirely erased but instead ends up in another dimension after an unspecified period. This theory is supported by evidence of unstable matter from The Backrooms being drawn into [[The Broken]]. However, it is important to note that '''The Broken''' attracts only unstable matter leaving The Backrooms, rather than all matter in its vicinity.

The frequency of Nullification is unpredictable but has increased in recent times for unknown reasons. The speed and effectiveness of the process are difficult to estimate, though, as mentioned earlier, the stability of the matter in question significantly influences the time required for complete Nullification. Despite this, certain anomalies suggest additional factors at play, as stable levels such as [[Level 330]] have undergone Nullification at an unusually rapid pace.

The visual effects of Nullification on objects vary. To the naked eye, it manifests as faulty openings or cracks scattered across the object, along with inconsistent blurring, shifting, and contortion of its texture. When recorded on camera, Nullification appears as black static, accompanied by glitches and buffering in the footage.

Nullification also affects biological matter, making it extremely hazardous to both humans and entities. If you find yourself near an entrance to The Void or in a level undergoing Nullification, you should seek a safer path or, if inside an affected level, immediately locate an exit.

There are rare instances where levels or matter gradually recover from Nullification, but this only occurs if the process is unusually slow and depends on the structural integrity and stability of the affected matter.
==<span style=font-size:23px;font-family: 'Space Mono' ;">Absolute Nullification</span>==
Absolute Nullification is a far less common variant of standard Nullification. Instead of matter gradually decomposing, it is instantly erased upon initial exposure. This occurs when highly unstable matter is rapidly introduced to The Void, causing it to disintegrate immediately.

Few instances of Absolute Nullification have been recorded, most notably affecting [[Level 330]] and '''Level 0.1'''. While larger and more complex structures still require some time to be fully nullified, the process is significantly faster than standard Nullification.

Another key difference is that any matter affected by Absolute Nullification can no longer be recovered. This stems from unstable matter having a lower likelihood of regeneration, and since Absolute Nullification occurs at an accelerated pace, any nullified matter remains permanently erased.
